\cf2 In China, {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.carbonbrief.org/analysis-coronavirus-has-temporarily-reduced-chinas-co2-emissions-by-a-quarter"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 emissions fell 25% at the start of the year}} as people were instructed to stay at home, factories shuttered and {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.axios.com/coronavirus-china-carbon-emissions-3453d9a1-1ae9-4789-8a41-3ed257946dbd.html"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 coal use fell by 40% at China\'92s six largest power plants since the last quarter of 2019}}. The proportion of days with \'93good quality air\'94 was up 11.4% compared with the same time last year in 337 cities across China, according to its Ministry of Ecology and Environment. In Europe, satellite images show {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.esa.int/ESA_Multimedia/Videos/2020/03/Coronavirus_nitrogen_dioxide_emissions_drop_over_Italy"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 nitrogen dioxide (NO2) emissions fading away over northern Italy}}. A similar story is playing out in {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://english.elpais.com/society/2020-03-24/pollution-in-spain-falls-to-record-lows-under-coronavirus-lockdown.html"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 Spain}} and {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.standard.co.uk/news/uk/pollution-falling-uk-coronavirus-lockdown-a4396051.html"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 the UK}}.\'a0\
Only an immediate and existential threat like Covid-19 could have led to such a profound change so fast; at the time of writing, global deaths from the virus had passed 20,000, with more than 400,000 cases confirmed worldwide. As well as the toll of early deaths, {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-51979245"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 the pandemic has brought widespread job losses}} and threatened the livelihoods of millions as businesses struggle to cope with the restrictions being put in place to control the virus. {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-51706225"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 Economic activity has stalled and stock markets have tumbled}} alongside the falling carbon emissions. It\'92s the precisely opposite of the drive towards {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.lse.ac.uk/GranthamInstitute/publication/the-economics-of-climate-change-the-stern-review/"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 a decarbonised, sustainable economy that many have been advocating for decades}}.\
A global pandemic that is claiming people\'92s lives certainly shouldn\'92t be seen as a way of bringing about environmental change either. For one thing, it\'92s far from certain how lasting this dip in emissions will be. When the pandemic eventually subsides, will carbon and pollutant emissions \'93bounce back\'94 so much that it will be as if this clear-skied interlude never happened? Or could the changes we see today have a more persistent effect?\
The first thing to consider, says Kimberly Nicholas, a sustainability science researcher at Lund University in Sweden, is the different reasons that emissions have dropped. Take transport, for example, {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.ipcc.ch/site/assets/uploads/sites/2/2019/06/SR15_Full_Report_High_Res.pdf"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 which makes up 23% of global carbon emissions}}. These emissions have fallen in the short term in countries where public health measures, such as keeping people in their homes, have cut unnecessary travel. Driving and aviation are key contributors to emissions from transport, {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.ipcc.ch/site/assets/uploads/2018/02/ipcc_wg3_ar5_chapter8.pdf"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 contributing 72% and 11% of the transport sector\'92s greenhouse gas emissions respectively}}.\
We know that for the duration of reduced travel during the pandemic, these emissions will stay lowered. But what will happen when measures are eventually lifted?\'a0\
In terms of routine trips like commuting, those miles left untravelled during the pandemic aren\'92t going to come back \'96 you\'92re not going to travel to the office twice a day to make up for all the times you worked from home, says Nicholas. But what about other kinds of travel \'96 might the cabin-fever of self-isolation encourage people to travel more when the option is there again?\
\'93I can see arguments in both directions,\'94 says Nicholas. \'93It may be the case that people who are avoiding travel right now are really appreciating spending time with families and focusing on those really core priorities. These moments of crisis can highlight how important those priorities are and help people focus on the health and wellbeing of family, friends and community.\'94\
If this change in focus as a result of the pandemic sticks, then this could help to keep emissions lower, Nicholas suggests.\
But there\'92s another way it could go. \'93It could also be that people are putting off long-distance trips but plan on taking them later,\'94 Nicholas says. Frequent flying forms a large part of the carbon footprint for people who do it regularly, so these emissions could simply come back if people return to their old habits. (
