\b \cf2 Historic epidemics
\b0 \
This is not the first time an epidemic has left its mark on atmospheric carbon dioxide levels. Throughout history, the spread of disease has been linked to lower emissions \'96 even well before the industrial age.\
Julia Pongratz, professor for physical geography and land use systems at the Department of Geography at the University of Munich, Germany, found that epidemics such as the Black Death in Europe in the 14th Century, and the epidemics of diseases such as smallpox brought to South America with the arrival of the Spanish conquistadors in the 16th Century, both left subtle marks on atmospheric CO2 levels, as {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://journals.sagepub.com/doi/abs/10.1177/0959683610386981"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 Pongratz found by measuring tiny bubbles trapped in ancient ice cores}}.\
Those changes were the result of the high death rates from disease and, in the case of the conquest of the Americas, from genocide. Other studies have found that these deaths meant that large tracts of previously cultivated land was abandoned, {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0277379118307261"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 growing wild and sinking large quantities of CO2}}.\
The impact from today\'92s outbreak is not predicted to lead to anywhere near the same number of deaths, and it is unlikely to lead to widespread change in land use. Its environmental impacts are more akin to those of recent world events, such as the financial crash of 2008 and 2009. \'93Then, global emissions dropped immensely for a year,\'94 says Pongratz.\
The reduction in emissions then was largely due to reduced industrial activity, which contributes carbon emissions on a comparable scale to transport. Combined emissions from industrial processes, manufacturing and construction {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.c2es.org/content/international-emissions/"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 make up 18.4% of global anthropogenic emissions}}. The financial crash of 2008-09 led to an overall dip in emissions of 1.3%. But {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.nature.com/articles/nclimate1332"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 this quickly rebounded by 2010 as the economy recovered, leading to an all-time high}}.\
\'93There are hints that coronavirus will act the same way,\'94 says Pongratz. \'93For example, the demand for oil products, steel and other metals has fallen more than other outputs. But {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.carbonbrief.org/analysis-coronavirus-has-temporarily-reduced-chinas-co2-emissions-by-a-quarter"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 there are record-high stockpiles, so production will quickly pick up}}.\'94\
One factor that could influence whether or not these emissions bounce back is how long the coronavirus pandemic lasts. \'93At the moment that\'92s hard to predict,\'94 says Pongratz. \'93But it could be that we see longer-term and more substantial effects. If the coronavirus outbreak continues to the end of the year then consumer demand could remain low because of lost wages. Output and fossil fuel use might not recover that quickly, even though the capacity to do so is there.\'94\
