\b \cf2 Force of habit
\b0 \
There are other, less direct ways that coronavirus could have a longer-term impact on sustainability, too. One is pushing the climate crisis off people\'92s minds, as the more pressing concern of immediately saving lives takes precedence.\
The other is quite simply making discussion around climate more difficult as mass events are postponed. {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://twitter.com/GretaThunberg/status/1238377012235927554"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 Greta Thunberg has urged for digital activism to take the place of physical protests}} due to the coronavirus outbreak, while the biggest climate event of the year, COP26, is currently still scheduled to be held in November. COP26 is expected to {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-scotland-glasgow-west-49650909"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 draw 30,000 delegates from around the world}}. The conference organisers are still working towards hosting the event in Glasgow, a COP26 spokesperson says, although they are in frequent contact with the UN and the current COP president in Chile, among other partners.\
There may be another way that the behavioural changes taking place around the world could carry over beyond the current coronavirus pandemic.\
\'93We know from social science research that interventions are more effective if they take place during moments of change,\'94 says Nicholas.\
A 2018 study led by Corinne Moser at Zurich University of Applied Sciences in Switzerland found that when people were unable to drive and given free e-bike access instead, {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://iopscience.iop.org/article/10.1088/1748-9326/aaad73"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 they drove much less when they eventually got their car back}}. While a study in 2001 led by Satoshi Fujii at Kyoto University in Japan found that when a motorway closed, forcing drivers to use public transit, the same thing happened \'96 when the road reopened, people who had formerly been committed drivers travelled by public transport more frequently.\
So times of change can lead to the introduction of lasting habits. During the coronavirus outbreak, those habits that are coincidentally good for the climate might be travelling less or, perhaps, {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.bbc.com/future/article/20200224-how-cutting-your-food-waste-can-help-the-climate"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 cutting down on food waste}} as we {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.bbc.com/worklife/article/20200304-coronavirus-covid-19-update-why-people-are-stockpiling"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 experience shortages due to stockpiling}}.\

\b Community action
\b0 \
One response to the coronavirus outbreak that has drawn mixed reactions from climate scientists is the ways that many communities have taken big steps to protect each other from the health crisis. The {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://theconversation.com/coronavirus-response-proves-the-world-can-act-on-climate-change-133999"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 speed and extent of the response}} has given some hope that rapid action could also be taken on climate change if the threat it poses was treated as urgently.\
\'93It\'85 shows that at the national, or international level, if we need to take action we can,\'94 Donna Green, associate professor at University of New South Wales\'92s Climate Change Research Centre in New Zealand, {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/18/world/coronavirus-and-climate-crisis-response-intl-hnk/index.html"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 told CNN}}. \'93So why haven\'92t we for climate? And not with words, with real actions.\'94\
But for others, such as Nicholas, the community action has sparked hope for the climate in the longer term. And Pongratz sees the time afforded by self-isolation as a good opportunity for people to take stock of their consumption.\
It\'92s safe to say that no one would have wanted for emissions to be lowered this way. Covid-19 has taken a grim global toll on lives, health services, jobs and mental health. But, if anything, it has also shown the difference that communities can make when they look out for each other \'96 and that\'92s one lesson that could be invaluable in dealing with climate change.\
